---

ðŸ” Understanding .filter()

âž¤ What .filter() does:

filter() loops through each element in an array
and keeps only those elements for which the callback function returns true.

It creates a new array (does not modify the original one).


---

âž¤ How it loops internally:

Letâ€™s say:

const arr = [2, 5, 8, 10];

Now,

arr.filter(greaterThanSeven);

This means JS will call your greaterThanSeven function once for each element in the array:

e (element)	Condition (e > 7)	Return	Included in new array?

2	false	false	âŒ No
5	false	false	âŒ No
8	true	true	âœ… Yes
10	true	true	âœ… Yes


âœ… So, the output is:

[8, 10]


---

ðŸ§  Why (e) is used in the arrow function

filter() calls your function with three arguments internally:

callback(element, index, array)

But usually, we only need the element â€”
so we write:

const greaterThanSeven = (e) => {
  return e > 7;
};

Here:

e â†’ stands for each element in the array (you can name it anything, like value or num)

=> â†’ arrow function syntax

e > 7 â†’ returns either true or false



---

âœ¨ Shorter Version

You can simplify this:

const greaterThanSeven = e => e > 7;
console.log(arr.filter(greaterThanSeven));

or even inline:

console.log(arr.filter(e => e > 7));


---

ðŸ’¡ Difference from .map()

Method	Purpose	Return

.map()	Transforms every element	New array of same length
.filter()	Keeps only certain elements	New array of fewer elements



---

ðŸ§¾ Example Output Full

If arr = [2, 5, 8, 10], then:

let newArr = arr.map(e => e ** 2);
console.log(newArr);  // [4, 25, 64, 100]

console.log(arr.filter(e => e > 7));  // [8, 10]


